docs.abstract: Investors have finally started to chase this year’s stock market rally, which has been driven largely by the Federal Reserve’s sharp turn away from steady rate increases.
docs.snippet: Investors have finally started to chase this year’s stock market rally, which has been driven largely by the Federal Reserve’s sharp turn away from steady rate increases.
docs.lead_paragraph: Just three months ago, investors were in a panic over the idea that the Federal Reserve might push borrowing costs too high and tip the United States economy into a recession. Now, Wall Street is toying with the idea that the central bank could actually be cutting interest rates by the end of the year.

headline.main: The Fed’s Rate-Raising Days Are Over. Wall Street Couldn’t Be Happier.
headline.print_headline: Dim View Was Just What  Investors Wanted to Hear

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s ability to get his revised North American Free Trade Agreement through Congress may hinge on a little-noticed provision governing intellectual property protections for new pharmaceutical products.

headline.main: Drug Company Protections Are Latest Stumbling Block for Nafta Rewrite
headline.print_headline: Protection for Drug Firms Holds Up Nafta Rewrite

docs.abstract: Wealthy people with multiple homes may try to establish residency in lower-tax states to reduce their bill. Advisers say it’s a complicated task.
docs.snippet: Wealthy people with multiple homes may try to establish residency in lower-tax states to reduce their bill. Advisers say it’s a complicated task.
docs.lead_paragraph: Every year around this time, people grumble about their tax bills. This year, taxpayers who lost the deduction for state and local taxes in the 2017 tax overhaul bill — mainly those in California and states in the Northeast — are going to grumble even more. And for some, that grousing has turned to talk of fleeing to lower-tax states.

headline.main: The Teddy Bear Test, and Other Ways to Pass a State Tax Audit
headline.print_headline: Can You Pass the Teddy Bear Test?

docs.abstract: The company’s stock dipped on Thursday after a California jury found in favor of a woman who claimed that asbestos in the company’s talc-based powders caused her cancer.
docs.snippet: The company’s stock dipped on Thursday after a California jury found in favor of a woman who claimed that asbestos in the company’s talc-based powders caused her cancer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Johnson & Johnson’s shares dipped on Thursday after a jury in California ordered the company to pay more than $29 million to a woman who claimed that asbestos in its talc-based powder products had caused her cancer.

headline.main: Johnson & Johnson Hit With $29 Million Verdict in Case Over Talc and Asbestos
headline.print_headline: Talc Maker Told To Pay Millions Over Asbestos

docs.lead_paragraph: When Boeing’s Dreamliner was grounded in 2013, it took more than $20 million and three months to fix the problem. The crisis over its 737 Max jet could be even harder to manage, given the incalculable reputational risk after two fatal crashes.

docs.abstract: Bruce Friedrich spent decades trying to persuade people to stop eating meat. When that didn’t work, he turned his focus to creating better alternatives.
docs.snippet: Bruce Friedrich spent decades trying to persuade people to stop eating meat. When that didn’t work, he turned his focus to creating better alternatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Bruce Friedrich used to be the guy who broke into fashion shows to splatter fake blood on the models wearing fur coats. That was when he wasn’t handing out pamphlets on campuses or creating videos to expose the grisly reality of meat production.

headline.main: This Animal Activist Used to Get in Your Face. Now He’s Going After Your Palate.
